<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1590,1976]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,350,1770,1795]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Distribution.</emphasis>
This is a widely distributed species, ranging from Central to South 
<collectingCountry box="[1112,1209,1770,1794]" name="United States of America" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">America</collectingCountry>
throughout Amazonia and Atlantic Forest, with the exception of northeast 
<collectingCountry box="[775,844,1806,1830]" name="Brazil" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Gardner" box="[858,1020,1806,1830]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" refString="Gardner, A. L. (2007) American marsupials. In: Gardner, A. L. (Ed), Mammals of South America, Volume 1. The University of Chicago Press, Chicago, pp. 1 - 126." type="book" year="2007">
Gardner 
<number box="[959,1020,1806,1830]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="2007.0">2007</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Despite its wide distribution, this is the first occurrence in the state of Tocantins, in central 
<collectingCountry box="[767,839,1842,1866]" name="Brazil" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1590,1976]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,390,1878,1903]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Natural history.</emphasis>
Only two males 
<taxonomicName box="[595,787,1878,1903]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Metachirus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nudicaudatus">
<emphasis box="[595,787,1878,1903]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">M. nudicaudatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were captured, both in Tomahawk traps on the ground. Each of these captures occurred in opposite banks of the Araguaia River, in upland forest areas.
</paragraph>
